#remove features weakly lelated to price
#sqft_lot, yr_built, long, sqft_lot15
data <- data[,-c(5,15,17,18)]
#multicollinearity
#use VIF to quantify the severity of multicollinearity

# If the variance inflation factor of a predictor variable is 4 
# this means that variance for the coefficient of that predictor variable is 4 times
# as large as it would be if that predictor variable were uncorrelated with the other predictor variables.

# VIFs start at 1 and have no upper limit. 
# A value of 1 indicates that there is no correlation between this independent variable and any others.
# VIFs between 1 and 4 suggest that there is a moderate correlation, 
# but it is not severe enough to warrant corrective measures. 
# VIFs greater than 4 represent critical 
# levels of multicollinearity where the coefficients are poorly estimated, 
# and the p-values are questionable.
# Check VIF for sqft_living and sqft_above. Their correlation was 0.88
model = lm(formula = price ~ sqft_living + sqft_above,
               data = data)
summary(model)

step.model <- train(price~., data = trainingSet.1,
                    method = "leapBackward",
                    tuneGrid = data.frame(nvmax= 1:10),
                    trControl = train.control)

# Bagging
#I first try this code, but it seems like the sample is too large
#get a small sample size to show the basic walkthrough
trainme <- data %>%
  sample_n(1000)

#train1 <- createDataPartition(trainme$price, p = 0.8, list = F)



model_price <- randomForest(price ~ ., data = trainme, mtry=10)

df <- data.frame(trees=seq(1, 500, 1),
                 bag_err = model_price$mse)

plot=ggplot(df,aes(x=trees))
plot=plot+geom_point(aes(y=bag_err),color="magenta", size= 0.5)
plot

#about 50 tress
#check the varibale importance
varImpPlot(model_price)

#the top important variables are lat, grade and sqft_living, sqft_living15, bathroom
#random forest
set.seed(42)
model2_price <- randomForest(price ~ ., data = trainme)

df2 <- data.frame(trees=seq(1, 500, 1),
                 bag_err = model_price$mse,
                 rf_err = model2_price$mse)
plot=ggplot(df2,aes(x=trees))
plot=plot+geom_point(aes(y=bag_err),color="magenta", size= 0.5)
plot=plot+geom_point(aes(y=rf_err),color="chartreuse", size= 0.5)
plot

#variable importance
varImpPlot(model2_price)

#the top importance variables are lat, sqft_living, grade, sqft_living15, bathrooms
